        default Vector<A> take(int count)
        Returns a new Vector that contains at most the first count elements of this Vector.

        Does not make copies of any underlying data structures.

        Use caution when taking a small slice of a huge Vector, as the smaller slice will hold onto a reference of the larger one, and will prevent it from being GC'ed.

        Parameters:
        count - the maximum number of elements to take from the Vector. Must be >= 0. May exceed size of Vector.

      • slice

        default Vector<A> slice(int startIndex,
                        int endIndexExclusive)
        Create a slice of an existing Vector.

        Does not make copies of any underlying data structures.

        Use caution when taking a small slice of a huge Vector that you no longer need, as the smaller slice will hold onto a reference of the larger one, and will prevent it from being GC'ed. To avoid this situation, use copyTakeFromIterable(int, java.lang.Iterable<A>) instead.

        Parameters:
        startIndex - the index of the element to begin the slice. Must be >= 0. May exceed the size of the Vector, in which case an empty Vector will be returned.
        endIndexExclusive - the end index (exclusive) of the slice. Must be >= startIndex. May exceed the size of the Vector, in which case the slice will contain as many elements as available.

      • wrap

        static <A> Vector<A> wrap(A[] underlying)
        Creates a Vector that wraps an array.

        Does not make any copies of the given array. The Vector will hold a reference to the given array, but will not alter it in any way.

        Since bearers of this Vector will be unable to mutate or gain access to the underlying array, it is safe to share.

        Since this does not make a copy of the array, be aware that anyone that holds a direct reference to the array can still mutate it.

        Type Parameters:
        A -
        Parameters:
        underlying - array to wrap
        Returns:

      • wrap

        static <A> Vector<A> wrap(java.util.List<A> underlying)
        Creates a Vector that wraps a List.

        Does not make any copies of the given List. The Vector will hold a reference to the given List, but will not alter it in any way.

        Since bearers of this Vector will be unable to mutate or gain access to the underlying List, it is safe to share.

        Since this does not make a copy of the List, be aware that anyone that holds a direct reference to the List can still mutate it. Mutating the List is not advised. Operations that change the size of the underlying List will result in unpredictable behavior.

        Type Parameters:
        A -
        Parameters:
        underlying - List to wrap

        Builds a Vector from an Iterable.

      • copyAllFromIterable

        static <A> ImmutableVector<A> copyAllFromIterable(java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Constructs a new ImmutableVector from any Iterable.

        The entire Iterable will be eagerly iterated, so be careful not to pass in an infinite Iterable or this method will not terminate.

        If necessary to guarantee immutability, this method will make a copy of the data provided. If source already is an ImmutableVector, it will be returned directly.

        Type Parameters:
        A -
        Parameters:
        source - an Iterable>A< that will be iterated eagerly in its entirety
        Returns:

      • copyTakeFromIterable

        static <A> ImmutableVector<A> copyTakeFromIterable(int count,
                                                   java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Constructs a new ImmutableVector from any Iterable, but consuming a maximum number of elements.

        The Iterable will be eagerly iterated, but only up to a maximum of count elements. If count elements are not available, then the all of the elements available will be returned.

        This method will make a copy of the data provided, unless source is an ImmutableVector and its size is less than or equal to count, in which case it will be returned directly. If source is an ImmutableVector that is greater than count in size, a copy will always be made, therefore making it memory-safe to take a small slice of a huge Vector that you no longer need.

        Type Parameters:
        A -
        Parameters:
        count - the maximum number of elements to consume from the source. Must be >= 0.
        source - an Iterable>A< that will be iterated eagerly for up to count elements. It is safe for source to be infinite.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableVector that contains at most count elements.

      • copySliceFromIterable

        static <A> ImmutableVector<A> copySliceFromIterable(int startIndex,
                                                    int endIndexExclusive,
                                                    java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Constructs a new ImmutableVector slice from an Iterable.

        The Iterable will be eagerly iterated, but only for the number of elements needed to fulfill the requested slice. If not enough elements are not available, then the this method yields as many elements that were available.

        If necessary to guarantee immutability, this method will make a copy of the data provided. If source already is an ImmutableVector, a slice of it will be returned without making a copy.

        Type Parameters:
        A -
        Parameters:
        startIndex -
        endIndexExclusive -
        source - an Iterable>A< that will be iterated eagerly for up to endIndexExclusive elements. It is safe for source to be infinite.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableVector that contains at most endIndexExclusive - startIndex elements.
